15 Days in Switzerland ⤵️✨

📌 SAVE for your visit 

1– Arrive in Zurich - Uber from airport to hotel (hotel stay @zurichmarriott) 
2– Sight seeing around Zurich via trams
3– Travel: Zurich to Lucerne via train (hotel stay @artdecohotelmontana) 
4– Day trip to Mount Pilatus 
5– Sight seeing around Lucerne 
6– Travel: Lucerne to Interlaken via Golden Pass train then Interlaken to Grindelwald via train (hotel stay @belvederegwald) 
7– Day trip to Lauterbrunnen via train 
8– Day trip to Iseltwald and Grand Hotel Geissbach via Interlaken-Lake Brienz boat tour 
9– Grindelwald First Mountain and Pfingstegg (easily accessible from Grindelwald)
10– Jungfraujoch: Top of Europe (easily accessible from Grindelwald)
11– Day trip to Interlaken via train for paragliding 
12– Travel: Grindelwald to Zermatt via train (hotel stay @matterhorn_lodge) 
13– Day trip to see Matterhorn via Gornergrat Bahn 
14– Sightseeing around Zermatt town
15– Zermatt to Zurich Airport via train 

We used public transportation A LOT and saved so much money by having the Swiss Travel Pass (see reel for this). So worth it. We also chose to have Grindelwald as our base to do day trips from instead of Interlaken (which most people do) because the views were more appealing than staying in another city.  Interlaken is more convenient for day trips transportation-wise but we didn’t mind taking the 37min train down from Grindelwald. 

Grindelwald is absolutely STUNNING and given the chance I would definitely stay there again.  We purposely made a light itinerary because we wanted to fully enjoy every place we went to and also give ourselves a chance to rest. We don’t hike but Switzerland is known for its amazing hiking trails!

Health is WEALTH✨

I know that a lot of us put our health on the back burner, especially when we’re focused on living our best lives while traveling.  We assume that we’re young and healthy. But how can we really live our best lives when some health problems don’t have symptoms? 

Heart attacks and strokes can be caused by high levels of bad cholesterol or “low-density lipoprotein (LDL)” in your blood —— often a symptom free condition. 

Do you know if your LDL is in the Safe Zone?! 

I recently got mine checked and it was not in the safe zone. Something that I definitely need to address so it doesn’t worsen. 

The Family Heart Foundation can help you learn about LDL levels. At no cost, their Care Navigation Center can help find a healthcare provider, provide information about treatment options and more. Visit www.LDLSafeZone.org to learn how the @fhfoundation can help you navigate towards a healthier you.

#LDLSafeZone #sponsored

14. Zurich

Did you know that Zurich has over 1,200 drinking fountains — one of the cities with the largest number of fountains in the world. It is also the largest city in Switzerland and is certainly full of charms, especially Old Town. We loved the view from Lindenhof and walking down Munster Bridge (both of which were filming locations for CLOY). 

Getting around is super easy with their efficient tram system. We enjoyed window shopping down Banhofstrasse, which is a beautiful street lined with high end stores. Although quite pricey, we loved the food at Zeughauskeller! 

We wanted to visit the Lindt Home of Chocolate Museum in Zurich but we didn’t have the time! If you’re a chocolate lover, this place is definitely a must see!

13. Lake Lungern 

The most stunning train view we’ve ever experienced!! This was aboard the Lucerne- Interlaken Express (part of the Golden Pass Line). Tickets are free with the Swiss Travel Pass but paid seat reservations are highly recommended. 

We read so many conflicting blogs about the best side to sit. Some said left and some said right. We ended up sitting on the right side leaving Lucerne and it was the BEST decision as we enjoyed amazing views of Lake Lungern AND Lake Brienz on the way to Interlaken.  If you look at the map after Meiringen it looks like lake Brienz will be on the left side of the train but the train actually reverses direction (or goes backwards) towards Interlaken so the lake will still be on the right side — if that makes sense 😆

Would you ride this train?!

5 Awesome Things to do in Lucerne✨

📌 SAVE for your visit to Switzerland 

1. Walk down Chapel Bridge 

The oldest covered bridge in Europe is FREE to visit. As you walk through, don’t forget to look up and admire the paintings on the ceiling depicting Swiss history. The tower alongside it served many purposes in the past— one as a prison and torture chamber. 

2. See the Lion Monument 

This monument was created to remember the fallen Swiss guards during the French Revolution. Their names are inscribed on the monument. Mark Twain also visited this monument in the 19th century. (Visit for FREE)

3. Visit the Glacier Garden 

FREE with the Swiss Travel Pass. Lucerne used to exist under a thick ice sheet. When this melted, glacial pots remained. These are unique geological features, which can be conveniently admired while in Lucerne. 

4. Ride the City Train

Tickets are purchased directly from the conductor and Costs 15 CHF (adults). Great way to tour the city in 45 minutes. Earphones are provided and the audio tour is available in 16 languages. 

5. Visit the Church of St. Leodegar

The oldest church in Lucerne dating back to the 8th century. We loved seeing the twin spires of this Catholic Church towering above Lucerne.

11. Mount Pilatus 

Legends were told that dragons with healing powers lived here and helped protect the townsfolk. 

It is one of the BEST day trips from Lucerne. There is a live cam that shows current visibility up on the mountain. Several hiking trails and transportation options available to get up the mountain. 

We LOVED the views from up there!! 

We chose the Golden Round Trip which started with the gondolas then the “Dragon Ride” cableway (seen at the start of the clip) and then on the way down we took the steepest rack railway in the world aboard the cogwheel train down the mountain and lastly rode a boat back to Lucerne.  This route can be taken the opposite way starting with the boat from Lucerne.  Plan to allocate at least 5 hours for this activity. 

Tickets for the Golden Round Trip start at around $115 and are 50% off with the Swiss Travel Pass. There are other ticket options available if you want to skip the different routes of transportation. 

Would you visit?!

Service+Comfort+Food >>>✨

↗️ SHARE with someone you’d fly Business Class with 

*In our flying in comfort era*

Tbh we used to think that business class was also as waste of money. Given the fact that you can take a lot more vacations with the money if you fly in economy. 

This was until my husband decided to bid for a seat in business class, won and then we had our very first taste of flight luxury 🫠😂. 

It’s not that we never fly in economy anymore. But we purposely choose dates and destinations with the most affordable business class ticket options — especially if the flights are >10 hours. 

We spend a large percentage of our income on travel.  You have to tell your money where to go instead of wonder where it went. Budgeting is a big part of being able to save for traveling.  My husband also recently started following points creators so we’re excited to start use points for flights!

MORE INFO ⬇️✨

📌 SAVE for future reference 

— GLOBAL ENTRY —
▫️ current application processing time: 4-6 months 
▫️ apply online 
▫️ requires an in-person interview 
‼️ You can renew within 1 year of expiration. If you submit a renewal before membership expires, you will continue to have benefits for 24 months afterwards, even if your renewal doesn’t get processed before the expiration date. BUT if you let it expire, you’d have to wait the regular processing time. 
▫️regardless of age, every traveler needs needs their own Global Entry membership (yes, even babies) 
▫️automatically includes TSA Precheck — so you’ll benefit from shorter departure and arrival lines 

— TSA Pre✔️ —
▫️ 3-5 days processing time (can take up to 60 days)
▫️ apply online and schedule an appointment for finger printing or 10 min in-person appointment that includes fingerprinting for background check 
▫️ no need to remove shoes, belts, laptops or light jackets 
▫️ shorter or no lines at departure gates 
▫️ renew at least 60 days before it expires 
▫️ children 12 and under can join a parent with Pre✔️ in the dedicated lanes 

— CLEAR — 
▫️Apply online and complete the set at the airport CLEAR Kiosk
▫️uses biometrics to verify identity 
▫️only available at approx 40 airports (TSA Precheck is available at over 200 airports) 
▫️you’re still required to take off your shoes at security 
▫️there are several credit cards that offer free or discounted memberships 

— MOBILE PASSPORT CONTROL —
▫️requires a free App on a smartphone or mobile device 
▫️MPC does not require pre approval. Users upload required documents on the app 
▫️ Travelers from Visa Waiver Program countries (ESTA users) with a prior United States entry will be eligible to use MPC as well
▫️there’s a dedicated line for MPC — usually much shorter than regular immigration line

We have CLEAR and Global Entry. 
Definitely WORTH IT!

Travel Tips Here ⬇️✨

📌 SAVE for your visit to Peru 

▫️Best time to visit is between April and October 

▫️Don’t forget to bring your passport to Machu Picchu as you need to show it along with your ticket to enter — make sure to secure it before your tour!  You can book your tickets online. 

▫️there are no restrooms inside Machu Picchu but there is one right at the entrance — requires payment of 2 soles 

▫️don’t get your passport stamped with the Machu Picchu logo, it invalidates your passport — most people have gotten away with the stamp for years but some get questioned/detained for having it 

▫️use and bring mosquito repellent. LOTS of it 

▫️bring a hat and water 

▫️hire a guide — you’ll appreciate it more 

▫️ Circuits 1 and 2 have the classic “postcard view” of Machu Picchu 

▫️expect symptoms of altitude sickness while in Cusco, Sacred Valley and Machu Picchu — shortness of breath, headache and sometimes nausea & vomiting. Take time to acclimate, bring medications and drink coca tea to alleviate symptoms 

▫️you can hike all the way up to Machu Picchu from Aguas Calientes or take the bus to the entrance

Seychelles Itinerary ⬇️✨

📌 SAVE for your beach bucket list 

The Seychelles is located off the coast of East Africa and has three main islands: Mahe, Praslin and La Digue.

It takes over 20 hours to get to Mahe, Seychelles from Los Angeles. We flew from Paris, which took about 10 hours. 

🏖️3 nights in Mahe

Where to stay: Savoy Seychelles Resort & Spa
What to see: Beau Vallon Beach, Anse Royale and Anse Takamaka, Sauzier Waterfall, Seychelles Botanical Gardens 

🏝️ 3 nights in Praslin

Where to stay: Le Domaine de la Réserve
What to see: Valle de Mai —UNESCO World Heritage Site, Anse Lazio, Anse Georgette
☀️Day trip to La Digue Island to see Anse Source d’Argent — one of the most photographed beaches in the world (first and second slides) 

Travel Tips: 
▫️Bring water shoes — protect your feet from lots of coral 
▫️if you get water sick easily, bring motion sickness medications 
▫️use reef friendly sunscreen 
▫️drink lots of water — we got heat exhaustion here 🥵 
▫️try octopus curry! We loved all their fish dishes as well 
▫️Tips are usually included in the bill in bars and restaurants — but you’re more than welcome to leave more for exceptional service 
▫️ Best time to visit for optimal weather and water conditions are April-May and October-November. June-August are the driest months of the year, but you also encounter the choppiest ocean conditions
